{"term":"1957","caseName":"Commissioner v. Stern","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1957/311","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 07, 1958 (Part 2)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13432","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Openheim, you may proceed.","start":0,"stop":7.896,"duration":7.9}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Barton.","start":7.896,"stop":8.519,"duration":0.62},{"text":"Mr. Openheim is in the next case, Your Honor.","start":8.519,"stop":10.691,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, pardon me.","start":10.691,"stop":12.686,"duration":1.99},{"text":"Mr. Barton, yes, you may proceed.","start":12.686,"stop":16.58,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Before -- Mr. Justice, may it please the Court.","start":16.58,"stop":21.794,"duration":5.21},{"text":"Before attempting to argue the -- to answer the argument of the counsel on the other side, I'd like to call the attention of the Court to our contention that the questions argued by petitioner are not properly before this Court.","start":21.794,"stop":46.282,"duration":24.49},{"text":"The only question in the Tax Court was whether the petitioner or the respondent rather, was a transferee of the assets of the estate of Milton J. Stern deceased.","start":46.282,"stop":63.977,"duration":17.7},{"text":"Now, that appears on page 4 of the record which is in the deficiency letter sent to Mrs. Stern, the respondent.","start":63.977,"stop":75.017,"duration":11.04},{"text":"And then, in the pleadings, in the petition, the answer and the reply the reference is made 25 times I believe it is to the liability of the respondent as transferee of the estate of the decedent.","start":75.017,"stop":97.059,"duration":22.04},{"text":"And that is what the Tax Court decided.","start":97.059,"stop":100.825,"duration":3.77},{"text":"If Your Honors will turn to page 16 of the record, it is argued and decided that the petitioner is liable as transferee of the estate of Milton J. Stern, deceased.","start":100.825,"stop":116.705,"duration":15.88},{"text":"Now, the argument has been addressed to the proposition of whether she is a transferee of the decedent.","start":116.705,"stop":126.006,"duration":9.3},{"text":"Of course, if these proceeds had been paid to the estate and turned over by the executor to Mrs. Stern, we've never would have gone into the Tax Court because necessarily, she would have been a transferee there of assets of the estate.","start":126.006,"stop":145.251,"duration":19.25},{"text":"Another question which does not -- was not contended for in the Tax Court and wasn't raised there was the question with respect to the cash surrender values of the policies.","start":145.251,"stop":158.705,"duration":13.45},{"text":"The only question down below was whether or not she was liable for the proceeds of the insurance.","start":158.705,"stop":167.347,"duration":8.64},{"text":"So on those two issues, we contend that those questions are not properly before the Court.","start":167.347,"stop":175.401,"duration":8.05},{"text":"I don't want to take too much time on that.","start":175.401,"stop":178.166,"duration":2.76},{"text":"I think that is --","start":178.166,"stop":179.316,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I ask you a question?","start":179.316,"stop":180.315,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":180.315,"stop":180.642,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean that on the first aspect of the Government's case, the Tax Court decided it under a mistake of time.","start":180.642,"stop":189.613,"duration":8.97}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think I meant to say that, Your Honor.","start":189.613,"stop":191.719,"duration":2.11},{"text":"What I said was the question presented to the Tax Court was whether the petitioner was a transferee of the estate of the decedent.","start":191.719,"stop":200.994,"duration":9.28},{"text":"Never any question presented the Tax Court as to whether she was a transferee of the decedent himself, and of course, there is an immense difference between being a transferee of the decedent and a transferee of the estate of the decedent.","start":200.994,"stop":217.338,"duration":16.34}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes but the insurance policies were never part of the estate.","start":217.338,"stop":221.511,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the insurance proceeds never were paid to the estate and as I said, if they had been and then had been paid over to this widow beneficiary, we never would even gone into the Tax Court.","start":221.511,"stop":231.116,"duration":9.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But surely, the Tax Court must do understood that the proceeds were payable to her under the policy.","start":231.116,"stop":238.454,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"The Tax Court did understand that I -- I'm sure the Tax Court understood it but the only issue presented was whether she was a transferee of the estate and that's what the Tax Court decided in the order.","start":238.454,"stop":249.829,"duration":11.38}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, isn't that just a short or long way of saying that she was a transferee, but --","start":249.829,"stop":255.704,"duration":5.88}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- I -- that may be the views, Your Honors, but I don't believe it is.","start":255.704,"stop":260.766,"duration":5.06},{"text":"I think if we have entirely different questions in the case as to whether it's a transfer of property in the form of proceeds or cash surrender values from the decedent, then what we would have if the question were whether she was a transferee of the estate of the decedent.","start":260.766,"stop":281.503,"duration":20.74}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":281.503,"stop":281.88,"duration":0.38},{"text":"Is there any difference between the transfer of the estate of the deceased, transfer of assets of the estate?","start":281.88,"stop":290.247,"duration":8.37}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon.","start":290.247,"stop":291.858,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What they said was the transfer of the assets -- the transferee of assets (Inaudible).","start":291.858,"stop":297.699,"duration":5.84},{"text":"I presume they met by that if that's the policy (Inaudible)","start":297.699,"stop":306.414,"duration":8.71}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if they had gone in the estates then no question would have ever risen, because necessarily she had been liable if the estate had gotten these assets and turned them over to her.","start":306.414,"stop":316.347,"duration":9.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Suggestion that should have gone.","start":316.347,"stop":319.44,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon.","start":319.44,"stop":319.962,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The suggestion is that it should have gone in the estate.","start":319.962,"stop":323.504,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it should have gone to the estate under the way the policy was set up because the policy was payable to the -- to the insured's beneficiary, the widow.","start":323.504,"stop":332.287,"duration":8.78}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless the Government's right -- it's the Government's right to trust fund.","start":332.287,"stop":336.087,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then --","start":336.087,"stop":337.03,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- they will transfer his asset, it should (Inaudible)","start":337.03,"stop":341.246,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course the Government doesn't even contend they were in his estate.","start":341.246,"stop":344.799,"duration":3.55},{"text":"They -- they only argued that he ought to change the beneficiaries so it did go in his estate the way I understand the argument.","start":344.799,"stop":351.178,"duration":6.38}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":351.178,"stop":353.42,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the cash surrender values are a different matter of course that -- the cash surrender values never either went into the estates, so we'd have the same question there.","start":353.42,"stop":363.413,"duration":9.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":363.413,"stop":370.98,"duration":7.57}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"It could not levy on it after his death.","start":370.98,"stop":372.902,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":372.902,"stop":375.395,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"It couldn't levy on it after his death.","start":375.395,"stop":377.203,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose that a 90 days of levy and the one appearing on the record 4, is it?","start":377.203,"stop":382.161,"duration":4.96}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"I think I said 4.","start":382.161,"stop":383.435,"duration":1.27},{"text":"Yes, that's the --","start":383.435,"stop":383.748,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's see.","start":383.748,"stop":386.332,"duration":2.58},{"text":"Page 4 --","start":386.332,"stop":386.563,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 4 in the first paragraph, constituting your liability as transferee of assets to the estate of Milton J. Stern.","start":386.563,"stop":397.568,"duration":11},{"text":"Now, most -- assuming the questions are probably before the Court, the Government's argument principally is predicated on the theory that there's the same kind of a transfer here as would be involved in the case of a estate tax.","start":397.568,"stop":415.508,"duration":17.94},{"text":"If Your Honors care to turn to page 10 of our brief, we have set out there the sections of the estate tax law, which in our opinion clearly indicate that proceeds of insurance were not the property of the decedent.","start":415.508,"stop":436.449,"duration":20.94},{"text":"For instance, 811 provides that the gross estates shall include all the value of all property at the time of the decedent's death.","start":436.449,"stop":450.26,"duration":13.81},{"text":"Now, in 811 (a), to the extent of the interest therein of the decedent at the time of his death.","start":450.26,"stop":457.084,"duration":6.82},{"text":"Now, that would be stocks or real estate or something he might own that would go to his heirs or to his executor.","start":457.084,"stop":466.674,"duration":9.59},{"text":"Now, when you get down to the next sections about life insurance, it doesn't say anything about the interest of the decedent in the life insurance.","start":466.674,"stop":474.78,"duration":8.11},{"text":"It says to the extent of the amount receivable by all other beneficiaries as insurance showing that Congress in enacting the legislation never considered that the decedent had an -- a property interest in the proceeds of life insurance.","start":474.78,"stop":493.831,"duration":19.05},{"text":"If that -- if the Congress have so considered, it wouldn't have been necessary to have incorporated these two sections about proceeds going to this executor or proceeds going to any other beneficiary.","start":493.831,"stop":506.112,"duration":12.28},{"text":"Now, Chief Justice Vinson, when he was on the Court of Appeals in the John Hancock Life Insurance case, wrote an opinion in which he pointed out the distinction I have quoted on page 11 of my brief.","start":506.112,"stop":520.57,"duration":14.46},{"text":"A paragraph of his opinion in which he shows that the statute has two lines he says.","start":520.57,"stop":531.049,"duration":10.48},{"text":"One is the interest of the decedent with respect to property which he makes the transfer.","start":531.049,"stop":537.267,"duration":6.22},{"text":"The other is insurance which goes to the beneficiary and he states that the statute proceeds to impose a lien on the estate property to the extent of the decedent's interest at the time of transfer or to the extent of the beneficiary's interest under the insurance contract.","start":537.267,"stop":559.842,"duration":22.57},{"text":"So it isn't necessary and this -- in the -- it's Chase National Bank case didn't hold that there was a transfer of life insurance proceeds from the decedent to the beneficiary.","start":559.842,"stop":575.224,"duration":15.38},{"text":"In that case, the Court said, it was the termination of the power to control of the insured over the policy at the time of his death which rendered the proceeds includable in his gross estate.","start":575.224,"stop":591.346,"duration":16.12},{"text":"Not because he owns the proceeds and by imperative reasoning not because he own the cash surrender values but because at his death, the power to change a beneficiary terminated and shifted the economic benefit of that policy into the hands of the beneficiary.","start":591.346,"stop":611.294,"duration":19.95},{"text":"And that the Court said in the Chase National Bank case was the basis for the tax.","start":611.294,"stop":617.295,"duration":6},{"text":"Now, there are other cases where there are properties included in the gross estate which the decedent doesn't own a property in at the time of his death.","start":617.295,"stop":631.661,"duration":14.37},{"text":"For instance, transfers in contemplation of death maybe made years before.","start":631.661,"stop":638.483,"duration":6.82},{"text":"Revocable transfers and interests in joint tenancies or tenancies by the entireties.","start":638.483,"stop":646.928,"duration":8.45},{"text":"They're all segregated in the estate tax law, separate and apart from the one section that refers to property in which the decedent has an interest showing that all kinds of properties may be included in the gross estates including life insurance proceeds with respect to which the decedent didn't own a property interest up to time of his death.","start":646.928,"stop":672.107,"duration":25.18},{"text":"Now, then the Eight and the Ninth Circuits in two different cases each which I have cited on page 12 of the brief have held that the fact that there is a transfer rendering property includable in the gross estate at the time of death has nothing to do with the transferee liability and in income tax case.","start":672.107,"stop":698.199,"duration":26.09},{"text":"And in fact, in that case, it was a tenancy by the entirety and joint tenancies and they said there wasn't any property interest that went to the survivor which constituted property under Section 311 of the Internal Revenue Code.","start":698.199,"stop":718.239,"duration":20.04},{"text":"Now, the Government in its brief in a petition for certiorari admitted that they couldn't get certain property and the joint names of the decedent and its widow that is some bonds and some real estate.","start":718.239,"stop":737.446,"duration":19.21},{"text":"Now, those properties were includable in the gross estate just same as insurance.","start":737.446,"stop":742.231,"duration":4.78},{"text":"So I don't see how there can be any distinction between properties of that kind and life insurance.","start":742.231,"stop":749.164,"duration":6.93},{"text":"As a matter of fact, life insurance is -- policy is a contract where the insured pays a premium in consideration for the payment of proceeds to his beneficiary.","start":749.164,"stop":764.189,"duration":15.02},{"text":"As soon as that policy is signed, the insurance company is liable for the full amount if the insured dies the next day which demonstrates, we think that when the insurance company pays the proceeds, the insurance company pays its own money and it doesn't pay anything that belongs to the insured.","start":764.189,"stop":786.934,"duration":22.75},{"text":"Now, as Justice Harlan this morning pointed out all five Circuit Courts of Appeals which are passive on this question have held that there's no transfer of proceeds and there's been no Circuit Court of Appeals that's held of the contrary.","start":786.934,"stop":805.243,"duration":18.31}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"When you say proceeds, you mean death benefit.","start":805.243,"stop":807.777,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's the proceeds of insurance within the meaning of the transferee section of the income tax law, Section 311.","start":807.777,"stop":818.548,"duration":10.77},{"text":"Now, I like just to make one statement before proceeding a little further, I understood the counsel to say that the record showed that the insured paid the premiums up to the day of his death.","start":818.548,"stop":836.034,"duration":17.49},{"text":"The record doesn't show in any respect who paid the premiums or how long.","start":836.034,"stop":841.94,"duration":5.91},{"text":"It shows that these policies were taken out in getting about 1910 up to about 1935.","start":841.94,"stop":849.309,"duration":7.37},{"text":"And the widow, the respondent here was made beneficiary in 1919, after they married and she's made beneficiary in the last policy in 1935.","start":849.309,"stop":860.414,"duration":11.11},{"text":"He died in 1939.","start":860.414,"stop":862.838,"duration":2.42},{"text":"There's no change in beneficiary between 1949.","start":862.838,"stop":866.909,"duration":4.07},{"text":"There's no -- no change in beneficiary from the time these -- from 1935 up to the day of his death.","start":866.909,"stop":874.972,"duration":8.06},{"text":"Now, these tax years are 1944 to 1947.","start":874.972,"stop":884.652,"duration":9.68},{"text":"The Court of Appeals below made the statement that there's no evidence of insolvency before death.","start":884.652,"stop":892.501,"duration":7.85},{"text":"There's no evidence that he took out these policies or maintained them to defraud, defeat the creditors.","start":892.501,"stop":900.444,"duration":7.94},{"text":"And I would say further there's no evidence whatever in the case as to whether the insured paid any premium from these policies during the taxable years 1944 to 1947, or after that -- after the date of his death.","start":900.444,"stop":917.31,"duration":16.87},{"text":"And as to all of that, the Government has a burden of proof under Section 1119 (a) because the Government has a burden of proving transferee liability and the burden is not on the taxpayer.","start":917.31,"stop":936.811,"duration":19.5}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the cash surrender value on the day of his death?","start":936.811,"stop":939.528,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the cash surrender value, it's been in the record.","start":939.528,"stop":941.6,"duration":2.07},{"text":"Let's say there are -- I think about $27,000.","start":941.6,"stop":947.506,"duration":5.91}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the payment of (Inaudible).","start":947.506,"stop":955.718,"duration":8.21}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"I think there are about (Inaudible) $47,000.","start":955.718,"stop":969.389,"duration":13.67},{"text":"The cash surrender value is $27,000 and the proceeds are $47,000.","start":969.389,"stop":974.919,"duration":5.53},{"text":"Now, that's on page 13 of the record.","start":974.919,"stop":976.759,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, is there any evidence in the record of 174 the tax (Inaudible) that he paid the premiums during the years when his estate is depleted?","start":976.759,"stop":990.265,"duration":13.51}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no evidence, Your Honor.","start":990.265,"stop":991.137,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Or why -- or through the premiums, he pleaded as a estate or surrendered (Inaudible).","start":991.137,"stop":998.183,"duration":7.05}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, there is no evidence whatsoever.","start":998.183,"stop":1000.632,"duration":2.45},{"text":"As I stated, there was a -- this case went to the Tax Court on a stipulation principally and there was no evidence, no statement made in the stipulation as to who paid the premiums or how long the period.","start":1000.632,"stop":1017.212,"duration":16.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean for all we know, she might have paid them?","start":1017.212,"stop":1020.504,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"For all you know, she might have paid them or for all we know, he may have paid them all in a lump sum in the beginning as far as the evidence goes.","start":1020.504,"stop":1028.175,"duration":7.67},{"text":"Now, the Tax Court said in the opinion they assumed that he paid the premiums because we stipulated, he took out the policies but there's no evidence, one way or the other as to who paid the premiums and I say the burden is on the Government under a case of this kind and the Government never produced any evidence with --","start":1028.175,"stop":1051.14,"duration":22.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Davis said that we may dispose of the case on the assumption of trying to put out the policy if he was not himself -- on the same basis of the two -- although the evidence in the record doesn't disclose it.","start":1051.14,"stop":1068.389,"duration":17.25},{"text":"That he paid the premiums (Inaudible) the right of the policy --","start":1068.389,"stop":1072.414,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Tax Court assumed that he paid the premiums.","start":1072.414,"stop":1075.273,"duration":2.86},{"text":"I don't believe they said up to the date of his death.","start":1075.273,"stop":1079.314,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the assumption that she might have paid them is not to be entertained.","start":1079.314,"stop":1083.411,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't like to say, I don't like to admit something that isn't in the records, Your Honor, because --","start":1083.411,"stop":1088.025,"duration":4.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But if it's in the record that he pays them --","start":1088.025,"stop":1090.249,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"It isn't in the record he paid them.","start":1090.249,"stop":1092.043,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not.","start":1092.043,"stop":1092.481,"duration":0.44},{"text":"But they made that assumption.","start":1092.481,"stop":1093.684,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"The Tax Court said that it was stipulated that Dr. Stern took out the policies.","start":1093.684,"stop":1101.12,"duration":7.44},{"text":"Therefore, we assume he paid the premiums.","start":1101.12,"stop":1104.403,"duration":3.28},{"text":"That's what the Tax Court said.","start":1104.403,"stop":1106.054,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose that instead of insurance $40,000 worth of personal property has been turned over to a custodian.","start":1106.054,"stop":1115.754,"duration":9.7},{"text":"Then he understands that the payment back if the man wanted to pay at the time of his death, $27,000 surrendered over.","start":1115.754,"stop":1128.086,"duration":12.33},{"text":"Otherwise, he was (Inaudible), would there be any difference from your position -- turned over to the widow (Voice Overlap)","start":1128.086,"stop":1136.541,"duration":8.45}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) -- If he turned this property over to the widow with the rights to revoke it --","start":1136.541,"stop":1142.506,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it's just -- sure.","start":1142.506,"stop":1146.05,"duration":3.54},{"text":"Turned it over to a custodian $40,000 (Inaudible) and with the understanding that it goes to the widow because he doesn't take anything back from -- before he died.","start":1146.05,"stop":1160.197,"duration":14.15},{"text":"But then after the very moment of his death, he can get in fact, $27,000 there.","start":1160.197,"stop":1165.701,"duration":5.5}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well Your Honor --","start":1165.701,"stop":1166.585,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any difference so far as the legal question that you're arguing?","start":1166.585,"stop":1170.714,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I don't believe it would and here's the case that I'm sorry I didn't find until after a brief was filed, a decision of this Court in Jones versus Clinton.","start":1170.714,"stop":1184.258,"duration":13.54},{"text":"Quite an old case but I think it's sound, 101 U.S. 225.","start":1184.258,"stop":1193.534,"duration":9.28}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"225?","start":1193.534,"stop":1194.739,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, 101 U.S.225.","start":1194.739,"stop":1199.424,"duration":4.68},{"text":"Now, the bankrupt made a voluntary assignment of all of these assets.","start":1199.424,"stop":1210.087,"duration":10.66},{"text":"Now, prior to the assignment, I don't know how long before but prior to that time and I don't believe there's any evidence, while the evidence was, he was solvent when he did it.","start":1210.087,"stop":1219.764,"duration":9.68},{"text":"He gave a deed to his wife of certain real estate and also included in this deed, certain life insurance policies but he kept in the deed a power to revoke it and take it back or a power to appoint it.","start":1219.764,"stop":1240.998,"duration":21.23},{"text":"Now, the question was whether when he made the assignment of all of his assets to the assignee.","start":1240.998,"stop":1248.714,"duration":7.72},{"text":"That included his power of revocation of that assignment to his wife.","start":1248.714,"stop":1257.387,"duration":8.67},{"text":"This Court held it did not.","start":1257.387,"stop":1260.41,"duration":3.02},{"text":"This Court said that power is not an interest in property which can be transferred to another or sold on execution or devised by will.","start":1260.41,"stop":1271.274,"duration":10.86},{"text":"The grantor could indeed escape the power either by deed or will, but he could not best power in any other person.","start":1271.274,"stop":1283.723,"duration":12.45}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be (Inaudible)","start":1283.723,"stop":1286.624,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that would be, yes, because -- yes Your Honor, the bank --","start":1286.624,"stop":1289.574,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"The Congress (Inaudible)","start":1289.574,"stop":1290.856,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"The bankruptcy law today provides that shall -- the bankrupt shall have title to all of the trustees, title to all property and that there shall be included all of the bankrupt's powers which he can exercise for his own benefit.","start":1290.856,"stop":1308.302,"duration":17.45},{"text":"So, that would be carried to the present time.","start":1308.302,"stop":1310.233,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Barton, may I assume Justice Black's question in a more practical if I may say so or more concrete aspect in Massachusetts and in one or two other states that you are (Inaudible).","start":1310.233,"stop":1330.861,"duration":20.63},{"text":"In Massachusetts, one of the key -- no, one of the important source of insurance writing is through the savings bank.","start":1330.861,"stop":1340.386,"duration":9.52},{"text":"They are authorized and have been for now what, 30 odd years or more.","start":1340.386,"stop":1345.156,"duration":4.77},{"text":"Writing insurance on the theory that insurance is nothing but a form of savings.","start":1345.156,"stop":1350.297,"duration":5.14}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor --","start":1350.297,"stop":1351.305,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And it has the basis of it in the vast amount as you probably know, a very great deal of insurance is written through the savings bank of Massachusetts.","start":1351.305,"stop":1363.602,"duration":12.3}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I --","start":1363.602,"stop":1363.992,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, that's between another form of the general question that Justice Black asked, as in this to be treated like money in the borrowing savings bank or whatever savings bank here.","start":1363.992,"stop":1376.976,"duration":12.98}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the reason, Your Honor is of course, I don't know what kind of a policy it would have in the savings bank, but the --","start":1376.976,"stop":1383.111,"duration":6.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":1383.111,"stop":1385.906,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"The --","start":1385.906,"stop":1386.057,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- you'll have somebody, your beneficiary will file the revocation.","start":1386.057,"stop":1389.929,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"The insured on a level premium payment plan as the counsel this morning stated pays more in the early years in the cost of mortality.","start":1389.929,"stop":1403.279,"duration":13.35},{"text":"The laws of the state require a solvency reserve, which is the excess over the level premium over the -- over the cost mortality and then with the accumulation of interest.","start":1403.279,"stop":1418.929,"duration":15.65},{"text":"Now, the cash surrender value might be equivalent to the reserve or maybe like deduct the cancelation charge, but the fact that there is a reserve doesn't mean that the insured owns that reserve fund.","start":1418.929,"stop":1436.127,"duration":17.2},{"text":"Now, if the insured wants to borrow money from the insurance company, it comes out of the reserve.","start":1436.127,"stop":1442.994,"duration":6.87},{"text":"He's got to pay an -- he got to pay an interest on that.","start":1442.994,"stop":1446.231,"duration":3.24},{"text":"Now, if that were his own money, he wouldn't have paid any interest on it.","start":1446.231,"stop":1450.189,"duration":3.96},{"text":"And the reserve fund under the law and investment of the insurance company, accumulates interests.","start":1450.189,"stop":1457.919,"duration":7.73},{"text":"Who pays an income tax without interest?","start":1457.919,"stop":1460.237,"duration":2.32},{"text":"It isn't the insured causing interest that goes into that reserve fund belongs to the insurance company.","start":1460.237,"stop":1465.853,"duration":5.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the fund of course, there's no trust fund in any sense of a reach in which part of it is mine but that's no more -- that's equally true or untrue of a savings bank account and any of the savings bank.","start":1465.853,"stop":1480.13,"duration":14.28},{"text":"Nobody owns an adequate cost --","start":1480.13,"stop":1482.362,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1482.362,"stop":1482.756,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the actual money in the vault.","start":1482.756,"stop":1486.315,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, the insured has a right to recover the cash surrender value of his policy if he surrenders his policy.","start":1486.315,"stop":1503.481,"duration":17.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's his, isn't it?","start":1503.481,"stop":1505.089,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon.","start":1505.089,"stop":1505.65,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's his because I've always thought of my --","start":1505.65,"stop":1507.684,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, (Voice Overlap) I believe that Your Honor is incorrect in that.","start":1507.684,"stop":1512.098,"duration":4.41},{"text":"Now, I have cited --","start":1512.098,"stop":1513.684,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I can get it today if I happen to have a policy that has --","start":1513.684,"stop":1516.8,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but you don't own that until you surrender your policy.","start":1516.8,"stop":1519.79,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I don't know -- I don't have the money in my hand but if the company is any good, I've got the right to give right away.","start":1519.79,"stop":1526.266,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but you can't get it except to surrender your policy and terminate your contract insurance.","start":1526.266,"stop":1530.138,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1530.138,"stop":1530.739,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1530.739,"stop":1531.306,"duration":0.57},{"text":"But that does not mean that you own that cash surrender value.","start":1531.306,"stop":1534.363,"duration":3.06},{"text":"You've got to surrender for the cash surrender value policy.","start":1534.363,"stop":1538.454,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, (Inaudible) equivalent of the cash surrender value.","start":1538.454,"stop":1541.87,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, well, that is -- that is true perhaps, Your honor, but then the question gets around to the proposition of whether the cash surrender value passes to the beneficiary at the time of the decedent's death.","start":1541.87,"stop":1558.364,"duration":16.49}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) -- whatever maybe -- whatever the cash surrender value (Inaudible) in Dr. Stern's lifetime, have looked to that pay the efficiency of an income tax with parole.","start":1558.364,"stop":1573.551,"duration":15.19}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if they had made an assessment, then a lien automatically would have attached to all of his property and I would say an insurance policy is a property.","start":1573.551,"stop":1582.29,"duration":8.74},{"text":"Now, first in this case, this tax wasn't assessed until almost six years after he died --","start":1582.29,"stop":1589.045,"duration":6.76}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The deficiency?","start":1589.045,"stop":1590.094,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"The deficiency.","start":1590.094,"stop":1592.921,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But require tax which he owed (Voice Overlap) --","start":1592.921,"stop":1598.742,"duration":5.82}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- yes, it's approved before his death.","start":1598.742,"stop":1601.176,"duration":2.43},{"text":"There isn't any doubt about that.","start":1601.176,"stop":1603.395,"duration":2.22},{"text":"Now then, we -- we have in our brief contended, there is no transfer of the cash surrender value or the proceeds.","start":1603.395,"stop":1611.324,"duration":7.93},{"text":"I don't believe the Government contends very seriously about the proceeds.","start":1611.324,"stop":1616.156,"duration":4.83},{"text":"The question there is the beneficiary, a transferee of property of a taxpayer.","start":1616.156,"stop":1623.349,"duration":7.19},{"text":"Now, they argue that by analogy, you can go to the transferee section under estate tax law.","start":1623.349,"stop":1631.537,"duration":8.19},{"text":"Well, the transferee section in the estate tax and the income tax law both originated in 1926.","start":1631.537,"stop":1638.884,"duration":7.35},{"text":"They read exactly the same way except in income tax, it said that the property of the taxpayer and the other said property of the decedent.","start":1638.884,"stop":1648.366,"duration":9.48},{"text":"Now, in 1918, was the first time that life insurance is brought into the estate tax.","start":1648.366,"stop":1655.191,"duration":6.83},{"text":"And in the same law, they made the beneficiary of the policy personally liable for the tax to the extent of the proceeds produced the estate tax.","start":1655.191,"stop":1671.701,"duration":16.51},{"text":"Now, that was 1918.","start":1671.701,"stop":1674.138,"duration":2.44},{"text":"In 1926, the transferee provision in both sections of the law were put into effect, and it was not until 1942 that Congress amended the estate tax section and brought in a beneficiary of an insurance policy although that beneficiary had been liable all these years from 1918 and of course in 1926 where the transferee section was first enacted They amended the law and made the beneficiary subject to the summary process of assessment, but that amendment did not make the beneficiary viable for the tax.","start":1674.138,"stop":1718.556,"duration":44.42},{"text":"The beneficiary is already liable under the former section and here under 827 (b), the beneficiary is liable.","start":1718.556,"stop":1727.289,"duration":8.73},{"text":"So, we say and as the Court of Appeals in the Rowen case in New York said, the fact that Congress didn't changed the law in the income tax showed that Congress didn't intend to produce the same result that they did in the estate tax when they did amend the law.","start":1727.289,"stop":1750.354,"duration":23.07},{"text":"Now, then if we should be wrong --","start":1750.354,"stop":1751.281,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That argument -- that argument does depend on whether she is a transferee or not, does it?","start":1751.281,"stop":1756.326,"duration":5.05},{"text":"But you're saying there is that Congress is taking hold of this thing and legislate it but they didn't choose to pose a liability under the (Inaudible)","start":1756.326,"stop":1766.05,"duration":9.72}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the liability of the beneficiary of life insurance was already existent in the case of the estate taxes, it had been from 1918.","start":1766.05,"stop":1777.228,"duration":11.18},{"text":"So, all Congress did in 1942 was not to make the beneficiary liable but to bring the beneficiary under that summary procedure.","start":1777.228,"stop":1785.262,"duration":8.03}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then is your case based entirely on whether -- it was (Inaudible) then entirely on whether we agree with you that she's not a transferee?","start":1785.262,"stop":1794.516,"duration":9.25}]},{"speakerName":"Walter E. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you should hold that she is a transferee then we've got to find out what is the transferee liability.","start":1794.516,"stop":1804.512,"duration":10},{"text":"And there, we say, you have to look at estate law.","start":1804.512,"stop":1807.213,"duration":2.7},{"text":"Now, the only Court that's held that state law doesn't apply is in the Bess case which is going to be argued right away and I don't want to go into that too much, but that New Jersey law was almost word for word like the Kentucky law and the Third Circuit in the Bess case said that if you look to the state law of New Jersey.","start":1807.213,"stop":1834.171,"duration":26.96},{"text":"The widow beneficiary is not liable for the tax of the decedent but the Court in the Bess case says you don't look to state law, you look to general law, but I don't know where you look for the general law.","start":1834.171,"stop":1850.598,"duration":16.43},{"text":"That's what the Court said up in the Rowen case.","start":1850.598,"stop":1854.763,"duration":4.16},{"text":"The Third Circuit didn't point out any law you looked to but we say that you got to look the state law under the Kentucky law.","start":1854.763,"stop":1862.964,"duration":8.2},{"text":"There's no liability.","start":1862.964,"stop":1865.507,"duration":2.54}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 07, 1958 (Part 1)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13539","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 311, Commissioner of Internal Revenue, Petitioner versus Jean F. Stern.","start":0,"stop":22.478,"duration":22.48},{"text":"Mr. Davis.","start":22.478,"stop":25.317,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, if the Court please.","start":25.317,"stop":33.384,"duration":8.07},{"text":"The issue in this case and in the next case which follows is whether when a person dies leaving an estate which is insufficient to meet income taxes which he incurred while alive, whether the United States can recover and collect from the beneficiaries of his life insurance.","start":33.384,"stop":60.319,"duration":26.94},{"text":"Now, this question can be further divided into whether the beneficiary, if liable at all, is liable to the full extent of the receipts from the insurance company or whether it might -- the beneficiary might be limited in liability to the cash surrender value of the policies which the insured might have reduced the possession during his life.","start":60.319,"stop":88.161,"duration":27.84}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"All three cases fall in one of those two categories?","start":88.161,"stop":91.081,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":91.081,"stop":91.511,"duration":0.43},{"text":"There are really only two cases Mr. Chief Justice.","start":91.511,"stop":94.327,"duration":2.82},{"text":"It's this case and then there's petition on cross petition in the Bess case.","start":94.327,"stop":99.77,"duration":5.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't know there are.","start":99.77,"stop":101.615,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"There are good many other cases which have been decided on this issue, but before this Court at present time are these two cases.","start":101.615,"stop":108.322,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean a lot of (Inaudible)","start":108.322,"stop":110.842,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"And it was the question of whether the -- a question further in state law or federal law?","start":110.842,"stop":116.056,"duration":5.21}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":116.056,"stop":116.586,"duration":0.53},{"text":"That's one of the basic problems in this case.","start":116.586,"stop":121.965,"duration":5.38},{"text":"Now, the facts in this case are not in dispute.","start":121.965,"stop":124.495,"duration":2.53},{"text":"After Dr. Stern died in 1949, they discovered that he had been cheating on his income tax.","start":124.495,"stop":133.863,"duration":9.37},{"text":"A substantial liability including fraud penalties was adjudicated against him in the Tax Court and the amount of that liability is not in question here.","start":133.863,"stop":146.949,"duration":13.09},{"text":"At the time of his death, Dr. Stern had enforced 17 life insurance policies which had accumulated a substantial cash surrender values.","start":146.949,"stop":160.781,"duration":13.83},{"text":"His wife was named as beneficiary in each one of these insurance policies, but Dr. Stern has retained the right to assign the policies, to change the beneficiary, to borrow against the cash surrender value or to surrender the policies entirely.","start":160.781,"stop":181.32,"duration":20.54},{"text":"Since they were insufficient assets in Dr. Stern's estate to meet his income taxes, the United States attempted to collect these taxes from the beneficiary of his life -- of his life insurance on the ground that she was an assignee, a transferee of these -- of this property from him and that since it was assigned to her without consideration when the taxes couldn't be paid that the United States was entitled to follow these assets in different hands.","start":181.32,"stop":214.31,"duration":32.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Was he insolvent from the policies that are taken out and when the opinion is made?","start":214.31,"stop":219.064,"duration":4.75}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I think we can assume that he was, at least the United States has not proved that he wasn't.","start":219.064,"stop":223.476,"duration":4.41},{"text":"So, the purposes of this case, it can be assumed he was so.","start":223.476,"stop":229.623,"duration":6.15},{"text":"Mrs. Stern submitted the question of her liability to the Tax Court and the Tax Court found that she was liable up to the full amount of the insurance benefits that she had received.","start":229.623,"stop":244.327,"duration":14.7},{"text":"She then appealed to the Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit and the Sixth Circuit reversed the Tax Court on the ground that a widow is not a transferee with respect to insurance policies and in addition, that under Kentucky law, a widow, a beneficiary of insurance cannot be liable for her husband's death.","start":244.327,"stop":270.307,"duration":25.98},{"text":"Since this decision was in conflict, at least in part with the case of United States against Bess which was decided in the Third Circuit.","start":270.307,"stop":279.51,"duration":9.2},{"text":"The United States petitioned for certiorari and that's why we are here.","start":279.51,"stop":285.735,"duration":6.23},{"text":"Now, just a word about the nature of these policies that were involved, there were 17 of them and they were not termed insurance which is pure insurance in the sense that there is no savings element in it.","start":285.735,"stop":299.181,"duration":13.45},{"text":"These were ordinary life insurance policies under which the insured pays a amount in excess of the pure insurance cost during the early years of the policy and a reserved accumulates which he, under his insurance contract, is entitled to borrow against or in case he surrenders the policy, he's entitled to withdraw the cash surrender value in full.","start":299.181,"stop":329.425,"duration":30.24},{"text":"Now, also with -- with respect to these policies, the insured retain full control to change the beneficiary at any time up to his death or to assign the policy.","start":329.425,"stop":342.534,"duration":13.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Are there any of the policies taken out that might be involved?","start":342.534,"stop":346.313,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry, Mr. --","start":346.313,"stop":346.974,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Any of the policies taken out and the tax is involved?","start":346.974,"stop":350.624,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"No, they are all -- they all anteceded the tax here is involved.","start":350.624,"stop":355.32,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I supposed, the premiums were paid (Voice Overlap) --","start":355.32,"stop":357.019,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Premiums were paid up until the time -- were paid by Dr. Stern up to the time of his death.","start":357.019,"stop":365.124,"duration":8.11},{"text":"Now, the courts have reached diverse results in cases on substantially similar cases -- similar facts to this.","start":365.124,"stop":373.988,"duration":8.86},{"text":"The Tax Court has uniformly held that the beneficiary of such insurance is liable to the -- to the full amount of the principal amount of the insurance paid to the beneficiary.","start":373.988,"stop":387.436,"duration":13.45},{"text":"The Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit has held that the beneficiary is liable but only to the extent of a cash surrender value of the policies which the insured could have reduced the possession during his life time.","start":387.436,"stop":402.327,"duration":14.89},{"text":"The Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit has held that there is, in fact, a transfer from the insured to the beneficiary of a cash surrender value, but it's held that the beneficiary is not liable because liability is governed by New York law and under New York law, the insurance goes to the beneficiary free and clear of death.","start":402.327,"stop":426.748,"duration":24.42},{"text":"The Fifth, Sixth and Seventh Circuits have held that the insurance beneficiary is under no liability to the Government at all.","start":426.748,"stop":437.412,"duration":10.66},{"text":"Now, basically, the results in these cases do not rest upon any particular language in the Internal Revenue Code.","start":437.412,"stop":445.964,"duration":8.55},{"text":"This particular action was brought under a Section called Section 311 of the 1939 Code which is merely a Section which provides for the procedure of collecting a liability against the transferee.","start":445.964,"stop":461.873,"duration":15.91},{"text":"It is uniformly agreed in the cases that Section 311 does not itself establish the liability.","start":461.873,"stop":469.123,"duration":7.25},{"text":"The basis for the Government's claim in these cases is the so-called trust fund doctrine and that in very simple words is, that when a debtor transfers part of his assets to a third person without consideration at a time when he is insolvent or when this transfer will -- a transfer will make him insolvent that the creditor can follow those assets into the hands of the transferee.","start":469.123,"stop":501.726,"duration":32.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And is that trust fund doctrine that you say isn't a derogative of any provisions of the tax act?","start":501.726,"stop":510.801,"duration":9.07}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":510.801,"stop":511.363,"duration":0.56},{"text":"There's nothing in the tax --","start":511.363,"stop":512.136,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Therefore, you -- you get it when?","start":512.136,"stop":516.482,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, originally, you'll get it from 13 Elizabeth 5, but it is part of our law at the time -- it's always been recognized as part of our equity law since --","start":516.482,"stop":527.611,"duration":11.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean switching sizes of the --","start":527.611,"stop":530.641,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, both state and federal law so far as I know.","start":530.641,"stop":534.596,"duration":3.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, -- and you climb up against the state and federal law (Inaudible)?","start":534.596,"stop":538.966,"duration":4.37}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":538.966,"stop":539.57,"duration":0.6},{"text":"We've got --","start":539.57,"stop":539.893,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And then where do you get it because you have answered impliedly that federal law prevails, is that right?","start":539.893,"stop":547.147,"duration":7.25}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":547.147,"stop":547.725,"duration":0.58},{"text":"Well, yes.","start":547.725,"stop":548.148,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And federal law is taken out of the interior, is it, common law interior?","start":548.148,"stop":552.904,"duration":4.76}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":552.904,"stop":553.415,"duration":0.51},{"text":"It is something that the collection -- when a debt is -- when the debt is established under the -- under the primary death is established under the tax law, of course, and the question of who is liable for that debt and how one goes about obtaining it, is how the courts enforced in effect, how they enforce that liability against whom they will enforce it.","start":553.415,"stop":576.087,"duration":22.67}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"If you're -- if you're under 13 Elizabeth theory, you can pretty narrow -- running a pretty narrow channel I would think.","start":576.087,"stop":583.427,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it certainly does --","start":583.427,"stop":584.189,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Does -- you can't -- there is no evidence in this record that back in 1919 that this man was insolvent when he's paying clemency there.","start":584.189,"stop":592.45,"duration":8.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You assumed the contrary?","start":592.45,"stop":593.757,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":593.757,"stop":594.2,"duration":0.44},{"text":"I assume the contrary.","start":594.2,"stop":595.576,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"You assumed that he was insolvent?","start":595.576,"stop":596.905,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That he was solvent at the time he paid the -- at the time he took out the contract and at the time he paid the premiums, I am assuming that he is insolvent.","start":596.905,"stop":604.739,"duration":7.83}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So, you're going after only payments, premium payments made while he was insured?","start":604.739,"stop":608.205,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"No -- no.","start":608.205,"stop":609.023,"duration":0.82},{"text":"I am going after the transfer of either the entire amount of the policy or the cash surrender value on the ground that this was a property of the taxpayer which was transferred to the beneficiary at the time of the taxpayer's death.","start":609.023,"stop":624.902,"duration":15.88}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's certainly a large ballooning of 13 Elizabeth.","start":624.902,"stop":627.179,"duration":2.28},{"text":"I just --","start":627.179,"stop":628.779,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":628.779,"stop":629.053,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I haven't looked at that.","start":629.053,"stop":630.635,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, a big problem if you went back to 13 Elizabeth itself would be intent to defraud.","start":630.635,"stop":635.753,"duration":5.12}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"This was the 14 Elizabeth?","start":635.753,"stop":637.176,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"[Laughter]","start":637.176,"stop":638.789,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Or Elizabeth the second.","start":638.789,"stop":640.763,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"It's Elizabeth one.","start":640.763,"stop":641.985,"duration":1.22},{"text":"[Laughter] Now, the original Fraudulent Conveyance Act involved intentional defrauding of creditors, then as it has been developed in the law, when a -- when a debtor is insolvent and transfers part of his property without consideration, it has been held that you don't go into the intent that you just -- that an insolvent person just can't transfer --","start":641.985,"stop":673.196,"duration":31.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"When was the transfer made?","start":673.196,"stop":674.823,"duration":1.63},{"text":"You have to fix a time.","start":674.823,"stop":675.654,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- we have -- in order to establish our case, the transfer would have to take place at the time of the death of the taxpayer.","start":675.654,"stop":681.923,"duration":6.27}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did he make the transfer before the time of his death?","start":681.923,"stop":685.372,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"The transfer occurred at the time of the death.","start":685.372,"stop":687.507,"duration":2.13},{"text":"I'm not sure that you could say that he did it, but it --","start":687.507,"stop":689.969,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he has to do it.","start":689.969,"stop":691.782,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"He -- he --","start":691.782,"stop":692.388,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"He died --","start":692.388,"stop":692.718,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"He took no voluntary -- he took no affirmative act.","start":692.718,"stop":696.464,"duration":3.75},{"text":"He -- up until the time of his death, he had a -- let's take the face value.","start":696.464,"stop":701.194,"duration":4.73}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Circumstances (Inaudible) --","start":701.194,"stop":704.035,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":704.035,"stop":704.178,"duration":0.14},{"text":"Well, I'm -- I'm certainly -- this is the origin of -- of the trust fund doctrine.","start":704.178,"stop":708.659,"duration":4.48},{"text":"It's a --","start":708.659,"stop":708.711,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Which -- which derived from fraud, is that right?","start":708.711,"stop":713.882,"duration":5.17}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"It derives from fraud.","start":713.882,"stop":714.714,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And then you say, that doctrine has bloomed and blossomed and grown so that now fraud is a fiction and by operation of law, she gets the benefit which she ultimately hold on to because he died insolvent, is that right?","start":714.714,"stop":729.584,"duration":14.87}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":729.584,"stop":730.961,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he voluntarily transferred?","start":730.961,"stop":732.658,"duration":1.7},{"text":"Is that -- that your argument?","start":732.658,"stop":733.994,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"My -- my argument is that he had the power up until the time he died to transferred this to anybody else.","start":733.994,"stop":745.054,"duration":11.06},{"text":"This -- she was temporarily named.","start":745.054,"stop":746.862,"duration":1.81},{"text":"She had a -- a right which could be divested.","start":746.862,"stop":750.393,"duration":3.53},{"text":"It is a power of -- in effect -- a thing that you have in a power of appointment so that her right matured, whatever rights he retained were transferred at that time of his death.","start":750.393,"stop":762.934,"duration":12.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, her right -- her right originated way back, isn't it?","start":762.934,"stop":767.727,"duration":4.79}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"A right, yes.","start":767.727,"stop":768.648,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"A right.","start":768.648,"stop":769.091,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"A tentative right to be --","start":769.091,"stop":769.911,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"A tentative right.","start":769.911,"stop":770.863,"duration":0.95},{"text":"You say that, when he died insolvent, he should have exercised the power of appointment in favor of Uncle Sam as the tax collector.","start":770.863,"stop":778.626,"duration":7.76},{"text":"That's really what this mean.","start":778.626,"stop":779.292,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- well, I'm not going into whether he should or whether he shouldn't.","start":779.292,"stop":782.596,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but that's what the law will do.","start":782.596,"stop":784.06,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is the effect of the law, yes.","start":784.06,"stop":786.254,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":786.254,"stop":791.063,"duration":4.81}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I don't think there was any voluntary act, they arose instead that of -- he didn't exercise his power in any other way.","start":791.063,"stop":799.535,"duration":8.47},{"text":"He had a power to move it to somebody else and he died.","start":799.535,"stop":802.515,"duration":2.98},{"text":"I don't call that a voluntary act.","start":802.515,"stop":804.107,"duration":1.59},{"text":"It is the act which caused his -- his death.","start":804.107,"stop":807.76,"duration":3.65},{"text":"If we run into this same sort of problem and the Court is meted with respect to insurance policy, with respect to estate taxes.","start":807.76,"stop":816.923,"duration":9.16},{"text":"The -- the law -- the state law includes in a decedents gross estate, certain insurance policies as to which he retained certain powers of ownership such as changing the beneficiary.","start":816.923,"stop":834.902,"duration":17.98},{"text":"And soon after the -- the Act was passed, it was attacked on the ground that the decedent didn't really transfer anything, that he didn't own the policy.","start":834.902,"stop":844.953,"duration":10.05},{"text":"He just taken out a -- a third party contract and when he died, these rights originated and came to the beneficiary.","start":844.953,"stop":852.496,"duration":7.54},{"text":"And this Court in determining whether or not the state law passed said, that there was in effect a transfer which occurs because of the death of -- of the -- of the person to be taxed in that case and I submit that it's the same kind of a transfer which occurs here.","start":852.496,"stop":871.626,"duration":19.13},{"text":"Here is a man that has certain rights which -- and as to the cash surrender value.","start":871.626,"stop":875.772,"duration":4.15},{"text":"He can actually reduce the amount of money, the actual possession.","start":875.772,"stop":879.89,"duration":4.12},{"text":"He dies, the rights passed to -- to the beneficiary and the question is can we follow them?","start":879.89,"stop":884.943,"duration":5.05}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":884.943,"stop":885.371,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"To use the same kind of the (Inaudible) is that right?","start":885.371,"stop":903.727,"duration":18.36}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That there was a transfer.","start":903.727,"stop":905.035,"duration":1.31},{"text":"That is all I'm raising it for, that there is a transfer.","start":905.035,"stop":908.713,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now (Inaudible) transfer here is a remedial enforcement of some Governments part, there somebody who got something in case of death (Inaudible)","start":908.713,"stop":923.816,"duration":15.1}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right and you have to find that the -- that there is a transfer.","start":923.816,"stop":927.879,"duration":4.06},{"text":"Maybe this was would be clear if I approached it first from the point of view of the cash surrender value itself.","start":927.879,"stop":934.082,"duration":6.2},{"text":"The --","start":934.082,"stop":935.957,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I ask you one question?","start":935.957,"stop":936.832,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":936.832,"stop":937.503,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"We had this in the Rowen case, of course --","start":937.503,"stop":939.104,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":939.104,"stop":939.643,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"in the Court of Appeals.","start":939.643,"stop":942.21,"duration":2.57},{"text":"There is no difference of opinion in any of the Circuit Courts on your proceeds point, am I not correct?","start":942.21,"stop":947.802,"duration":5.59}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":947.802,"stop":948.029,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Or unanimous that your -- that your point of view --","start":948.029,"stop":950.117,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"But I'm wrong.","start":950.117,"stop":950.928,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- was wrong on that","start":950.928,"stop":951.915,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":951.915,"stop":952.545,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And the only split is --","start":952.545,"stop":953.398,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Except the Tax -- the Tax Court of course.","start":953.398,"stop":955.719,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Shift the Tax Court which has been obvious.","start":955.719,"stop":958.553,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"It has been --","start":958.553,"stop":959.285,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It is certain not a --","start":959.285,"stop":959.825,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"We've -- they think they're right.","start":959.825,"stop":963.863,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, there is a split on the surrender value point?","start":963.863,"stop":967.36,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":967.36,"stop":969.071,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"A split in two respects.","start":969.071,"stop":970.707,"duration":1.64},{"text":"Number one, a split as to whether even surrender value goes which the Fifth Circuit here held or not.","start":970.707,"stop":979.242,"duration":8.53}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":979.242,"stop":979.705,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And there's a split among the other Circuits --","start":979.705,"stop":981.365,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"The Sixth Circuit?","start":981.365,"stop":982.297,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The Sixth Circuit, I beg your pardon?","start":982.297,"stop":983.866,"duration":1.57},{"text":"And there is a split among the other circuits.","start":983.866,"stop":987.358,"duration":3.49},{"text":"We have in the Second Circuit where a state law applied over the surrender -- surrender value merged into the proceed and the Third Circuit is held that federal law applies although agreeing with the Second Circuit to surrender value carries.","start":987.358,"stop":1002.264,"duration":14.91}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":1002.264,"stop":1002.78,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's (Voice Overlap) --","start":1002.78,"stop":1004.948,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the state of the opinion.","start":1004.948,"stop":1007.994,"duration":3.05},{"text":"I'd like to -- I'd like to think my position can be made clearer if I point out some of the aspects of this cash surrender value, which it is our position, the insured had and transferred at the time of his death.","start":1007.994,"stop":1021.937,"duration":13.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)[Laugh]","start":1021.937,"stop":1026.056,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- this Court has -- has pointed out the similarity between the cash surrender value in an insurance policy and the savings deposit in a savings bank and the short analysis shows that -- that this is indeed sound.","start":1026.056,"stop":1044.54,"duration":18.48},{"text":"If a man wishes to ensure his life for $10,000 and takes out a term insurance policy and annually deposits in a savings bank the difference between the cost of a term policy and the cost of an ordinary life policy, he will in fact get the equivalent of taking out an ordinary life policy where the company itself accumulates the savings instead of -- is having to do so in a separate account.","start":1044.54,"stop":1082.103,"duration":37.56},{"text":"Now, if the man took out term insurance plus savings account, there'd be no question that on his death, the savings account would be -- could be reached for -- for his taxes or for any debt.","start":1082.103,"stop":1097.752,"duration":15.65},{"text":"The mere fact that he accumulates his savings with the same company that gives the insurance policy, seems to us to make -- to make no difference as to whether it should be subject to his debt.","start":1097.752,"stop":1109.562,"duration":11.81},{"text":"As a matter of fact, it has been held and I -- I think there's really little dispute about it now, that if it is ascertained during the insured's life that he owes these income taxes, the United States can recover -- during his life can recover the -- the cash surrender value of the policies.","start":1109.562,"stop":1132.685,"duration":23.12},{"text":"Sometimes, it's done through attachment and sometimes it's done through a separate third party garnishments to -- in which the insurance company is named to the -- to the party, but the cases generally hold that you can reach that cash surrender value and similarly --","start":1132.685,"stop":1147.727,"duration":15.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"During the lifetime.","start":1147.727,"stop":1148.896,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"During the lifetime and similarly in bankruptcy, the bank -- the bankruptcy statute includes the cash surrender value within the gross -- within the estate of the -- of the debtor although there are certain provisions so that he can keep them alive by making payments of the premiums to save the insurance, but it -- it is regularly recognized as an asset of the insured which can be reached in order to -- to pay his debts.","start":1148.896,"stop":1180.809,"duration":31.91},{"text":"And therefore it seems that it is something which materially he has and which if -- if we could ascertain the amount of income tax in time, we could have reached.","start":1180.809,"stop":1191.181,"duration":10.37},{"text":"And if it is transferred from him to somebody else at the time of his death, it would seem only reasonable that we should be able to follow it.","start":1191.181,"stop":1199.291,"duration":8.11},{"text":"Now, when you come --","start":1199.291,"stop":1199.854,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I take it Mr. Davis that your (Inaudible)","start":1199.854,"stop":1211.063,"duration":11.21}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that could be so except that would -- the exemptions statutes of most States provides specifically to protect the -- the beneficiary of the insurance benefits from predators of the -- of the deceased.","start":1211.063,"stop":1226.876,"duration":15.81}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Those statutes you say, if there are, do not apply to income tax (Inaudible).","start":1226.876,"stop":1231.223,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":1231.223,"stop":1231.784,"duration":0.56},{"text":"We would say that they were -- they were an exemption in the -- and the states have no -- no power to put in exemptions as to what the United States make a right.","start":1231.784,"stop":1241.015,"duration":9.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1241.015,"stop":1244.585,"duration":3.57}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"There is no --","start":1244.585,"stop":1245.773,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1245.773,"stop":1247.704,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"There is none as far as insurance benefits are concerned.","start":1247.704,"stop":1250.984,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1250.984,"stop":1255.239,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"A state tax?","start":1255.239,"stop":1256.703,"duration":1.46},{"text":"Insurance -- the insurance payments are included within the gross of estate of the deceased as part of the estate tax.","start":1256.703,"stop":1267.338,"duration":10.63},{"text":"If the insured retains this incident of ownership which were involved in this case of a right to change the beneficiary far down --","start":1267.338,"stop":1275.664,"duration":8.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"By special (Inaudible)","start":1275.664,"stop":1277.446,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1277.446,"stop":1277.979,"duration":0.53},{"text":"It is specifically, made part of the gross estate and that is why the case came up whether or not there was a transfer because if there wasn't a transfer, it was argued that there was a direct tax on the insurance and that it wasn't properly apportioned.","start":1277.979,"stop":1294.883,"duration":16.9},{"text":"And so, it became a constitutional question whether there was a transfer of these insurance benefits from the deceased to the beneficiary which would support an excised -- excised tax on the transfer and this Court held that there was sufficient of a transfer with respect to the entire -- face amount of the policy.","start":1294.883,"stop":1320.295,"duration":25.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1320.295,"stop":1328.737,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":1328.737,"stop":1329.331,"duration":0.59},{"text":"The estate tax is part of the -- if the -- if the insured retains this incident of ownership which are involved here, these incidents of power to control then this is part of the gross estate.","start":1329.331,"stop":1341.662,"duration":12.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1341.662,"stop":1345.36,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there are, there's a $60,000 exemption in the -- in the estate tax and if the insurance policy is part of the -- if the -- if the proceeds are part of the estate, they -- and don't exceed this -- there is a $60,000 and then there's a widow's exemption too.","start":1345.36,"stop":1362.246,"duration":16.89},{"text":"I mean, there are other exemptions.","start":1362.246,"stop":1363.731,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1363.731,"stop":1367.203,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"But not with respect to insurance as such.","start":1367.203,"stop":1369.681,"duration":2.48},{"text":"I mean, this was as an estate tax exemption which isn't specifically attached to insurance.","start":1369.681,"stop":1377.74,"duration":8.06},{"text":"There used to be -- there used to be a -- a volume exemption with respect to life insurance in the estate tax which is no longer there.","start":1377.74,"stop":1393.794,"duration":16.05},{"text":"Insurances in one way with respect to the -- the face amount of the policy, merely a third party contract.","start":1393.794,"stop":1405.925,"duration":12.13},{"text":"If A desires to give B an automobile and A goes to a dealer and pays him the price of the car and asked that it be delivered to B, in common powers, A gives B the automobile, even though A never had title to the automobile himself.","start":1405.925,"stop":1426.353,"duration":20.43},{"text":"He provided for a transfer, and that is exactly what happens in the case of insurance.","start":1426.353,"stop":1431.963,"duration":5.61},{"text":"The insured goes to the insurance company and provides that if he will pay the premiums, the price of the insurance from time to time, the insurance company will transfer the face amount of the policy to the beneficiary on his death, and if one must said it in that light by the mere questions of the -- of title are not important.","start":1431.963,"stop":1453.092,"duration":21.13},{"text":"It is a -- a provision for where he has bought and had delivered the insurance to the beneficiary.","start":1453.092,"stop":1463.567,"duration":10.47},{"text":"The court below --","start":1463.567,"stop":1464.652,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1464.652,"stop":1471.97,"duration":7.32}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"As far as I know, there is quite a list of cases going back quite away.","start":1471.97,"stop":1476.949,"duration":4.98},{"text":"I don't -- I don't know of any -- of any inconsistent actions by the Government.","start":1476.949,"stop":1483.256,"duration":6.31},{"text":"The court below, following Rowen, held that the liability of a beneficiary in a case like this is to be determined by a state law rather than by federal law.","start":1483.256,"stop":1500.406,"duration":17.15},{"text":"The Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit says the question of liability depends upon federal law and it seems to me really impossible that there could be an equitable method of collecting income taxes if liability is not determined by federal law.","start":1500.406,"stop":1521.175,"duration":20.77},{"text":"It is true that in some respects, income taxes can be affected by state law if -- if for example title is involved and the States determined title, then there is an indirect effect to the state law.","start":1521.175,"stop":1535.05,"duration":13.88},{"text":"We -- we know for example that a few years ago, the community property law in the western states resulted in a situation where a man and his wife could divide their income for the community property estate and couldn't in other state and this has affected taxes was a direct effect of the state law.","start":1535.05,"stop":1555.253,"duration":20.2},{"text":"But that's a very different situation from where the state law deals specifically with the question of whether there will be liability of A to B.","start":1555.253,"stop":1567.377,"duration":12.12},{"text":"If a State can say that the widow isn't liable under these circumstances, I don't know why a state couldn't say that a man's entire estate shall pass to -- all of his properties shall pass through his estate, free of taxes whether it would be insurance or anything else.","start":1567.377,"stop":1586.657,"duration":19.28},{"text":"And in this respect, each State could fight with the other to see what benefits it could gain for its -- its citizens against the -- against the federal tax collector.","start":1586.657,"stop":1597.881,"duration":11.22},{"text":"As a matter of fact, --","start":1597.881,"stop":1598.98,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Liabilities (Inaudible)","start":1598.98,"stop":1618.761,"duration":19.78}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1618.761,"stop":1619.482,"duration":0.72},{"text":"The -- generally --","start":1619.482,"stop":1620.247,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1620.247,"stop":1626.835,"duration":6.59}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"The form of these statutes is generally that the beneficiary shall get full title free and clear.","start":1626.835,"stop":1634.786,"duration":7.95},{"text":"It's stated affirmatively in that sense.","start":1634.786,"stop":1636.928,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1636.928,"stop":1645.59,"duration":8.66}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would -- I would have no doubt if they get titled, but I would have doubt that the states could by saying that they get it free and clear of any claim.","start":1645.59,"stop":1654.186,"duration":8.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So, at the time the inference was created, there is no (Inaudible).","start":1654.186,"stop":1661.697,"duration":7.51}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then we come back again, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, when the interest was created.","start":1661.697,"stop":1666.993,"duration":5.3},{"text":"If we go back to the time the insurance policy was taken out, out of premiums were paid then we -- we would have a very -- a very bad case because there's insolvency at that time.","start":1666.993,"stop":1677.628,"duration":10.63},{"text":"We have to treat it as though the interest matured at the time of the taxpayer's death.","start":1677.628,"stop":1683.513,"duration":5.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not talking about the insured.","start":1683.513,"stop":1685.034,"duration":1.52},{"text":"I'm talking about (Inaudible)","start":1685.034,"stop":1699.953,"duration":14.92}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that's right.","start":1699.953,"stop":1701.19,"duration":1.24},{"text":"And there's no question, they had -- some States say, a divested right subject to divest --","start":1701.19,"stop":1706.335,"duration":5.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1706.335,"stop":1707.843,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1707.843,"stop":1707.977,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1707.977,"stop":1710.142,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1710.142,"stop":1710.541,"duration":0.4},{"text":"It is a real interest, but it isn't a final interest and it doesn't -- and it doesn't really come down to cash from the bank until the man died.","start":1710.541,"stop":1718.483,"duration":7.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1718.483,"stop":1719.211,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's when the --","start":1719.211,"stop":1719.602,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The things that have life that full (Inaudible)","start":1719.602,"stop":1722.08,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1722.08,"stop":1723.552,"duration":1.47},{"text":"And that is the time when we say there is a transfer of -- of the insurance interest to the beneficiary.","start":1723.552,"stop":1732.221,"duration":8.67},{"text":"It's necessary that -- our case really depends upon -- upon the transfer occurring at that time or we -- or we have no case.","start":1732.221,"stop":1740.751,"duration":8.53},{"text":"I think that it's clear that the present state of confusion arises from the fact that the States have enacted specific laws of relation to insurance to protect widows and orphans and people who needs the benefits of insurance.","start":1740.751,"stop":1754.691,"duration":13.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And the Congress has done nothing about it.","start":1754.691,"stop":1757.687,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the question -- that is -- that's right.","start":1757.687,"stop":1761.031,"duration":3.34},{"text":"If there is -- that policy maybe a good policy and maybe Congress should have done something about it, but Congress hasn't provided this exemption.","start":1761.031,"stop":1769.126,"duration":8.1},{"text":"It's the States which should provided the exemption, and I think that the question is whether or not we should construe this language as saying that Congress has for some reason, without expressing it, adopted a state exemption.","start":1769.126,"stop":1785.613,"duration":16.49}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Congress reached the estate tax provisions but didn't reach it in the income tax provision, is it?","start":1785.613,"stop":1794.43,"duration":8.82}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Specifically, it's provided a transferee liability.","start":1794.43,"stop":1798.198,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Specifically?","start":1798.198,"stop":1799.19,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Specifically.","start":1799.19,"stop":1800.144,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"As a counterpart to the taxability of the proceeds of a -- of a policy (Inaudible).","start":1800.144,"stop":1807.803,"duration":7.66}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- that is right.","start":1807.803,"stop":1809.016,"duration":1.21},{"text":"And --","start":1809.016,"stop":1809.165,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Two things are companion provisions and the situation is wholly different, is it not?","start":1809.165,"stop":1815.01,"duration":5.85},{"text":"It comes in that respect at least when it comes to the income tax.","start":1815.01,"stop":1820.778,"duration":5.77}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"But when -- but when the --","start":1820.778,"stop":1822.524,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You have to fall back on some general law.","start":1822.524,"stop":1825.505,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1825.505,"stop":1826.758,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"John F . Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the legislative history of the inclusion of this provision and the estate tax said that they were not enlarging the liability, but merely making it specific.","start":1826.758,"stop":1835.805,"duration":9.05}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1835.805,"stop":1839.596,"duration":3.79}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Apr 7, 1958","petitioner":"Commissioner","respondent":"Stern","docket":"311","citation":"357US39(1958)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/357/39","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 9, 1958"}